SIMPLE: interest
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interest
<hw>In"ter*est</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interested</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Interesting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From
<ets>interess'd</ets>, p. p. of the older form <ets>interess</ets>, fr.
F. <ets>int⟦eacute⟧resser</ets>, L. <ets>interesse</ets>. See
<er>Interest</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To engage the attention of; to awaken interest in;
to excite emotion or passion in, in behalf of a person or thing; <as>as,
the subject did not <ex>interest</ex> him; to <ex>interest</ex> one in
charitable work.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To love our native country . . . to be <qex>interested</qex> in
its concerns is natural to all men.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A goddess who used to <qex>interest</qex> herself in
marriages.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be concerned with or engaged in; to affect; to
concern; to excite; -- often used impersonally.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or rather, gracious sir,⟦br⟧
Create me to this glory, since my cause⟦br⟧
Doth <qex>interest</qex> this fair quarrel.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause or permit to share.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mystical communion of all faithful men is such as maketh every
one to be <qex>interested</qex> in those precious blessings which any
one of them receiveth at God's hands.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To concern; excite; attract; entertain; engage;
occupy; hold.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Interest
<hw>In"ter*est</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>interest</ets>, F.
<ets>int⟦eacute⟧r⟦ecir⟧t</ets>, fr. L. <ets>interest</ets> it interests,
is of interest, fr. <ets>interesse</ets> to be between, to be
difference, to be importance; <ets>inter</ets> between + <ets>esse</ets>
to be; cf. LL. <ets>interesse</ets> usury. See
<er>Essence</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Excitement of feeling, whether pleasant or painful,
accompanying special attention to some object; concern; a desire to
learn more about a topic or engage often in an activity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Interest</xex> expresses mental excitement of
various kinds and degrees. It may be intellectual, or sympathetic and
emotional, or merely personal; as, an <xex>interest</xex> in
philosophical research; an <xex>interest</xex> in human suffering; the
<xex>interest</xex> which an avaricious man takes in money
getting.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So much <qex>interest</qex> have I in thy sorrow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 777 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Finance, Commerce)</fld> <def>Participation in
advantage, profit, and responsibility; share; portion; part; <as>as, an
<ex>interest</ex> in a brewery; he has parted with his <ex>interest</ex>
in the stocks.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Advantage, personal or general; good, regarded as a
selfish benefit; profit; benefit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Divisions hinder the common <qex>interest</qex> and public
good.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When <qex>interest</qex> calls of all her sneaking train.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Finance)</fld> <def>A fee paid for the use of
money; a fee paid for a loan; -- usually reckoned as a percentage;
<as>as, <ex>interest</ex> at five per cent per annum on ten thousand
dollars</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have told their money, and let out⟦br⟧
Their coin upon large <qex>interest</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any excess of advantage over and above an exact
equivalent for what is given or rendered.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You shall have your desires with <qex>interest</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The persons interested in any particular business or
measure, taken collectively; <as>as, the iron <ex>interest</ex>; the
cotton <ex>interest</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Compound interest</b></col>, <cd>interest, not only on
the original principal, but also on unpaid interest from the time it
fell due.</cd> -- <col><b>Simple interest</b></col>, <cd>interest on the
principal sum without interest on overdue interest.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interested</ent>⟦br⟧
